We have to get him back.”
Bolivia, which has no outlet to the sea, still has the memory of the loss of the coastline that went to Chile in the bloody conflict of the 19th century due to natural resources, as well as the desire to swim again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are now perhaps the strongest in decades, as Bolivia awaits an international court decision on October 1 after five years of deliberation.
“Bolivia has momentum, a spirit of unity and calm and, of course, it expects a positive result,” commented Roberto Calzadia, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the announcement of the ICJ decision on big screens across the country. They hope that the tribunal in The Hague will decide in favor of Bolivia, which, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile will force into negotiations to grant Bolivia sovereign access to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president, who faced opposition to his re-election next year, also has high hopes for a decision to be announced on Monday.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to make a decision in favor of Bolivia, and if this happens, then little will change.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, has no authority to award Chilean territory and said it would not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the ICJ decision, taken only six months after the final arguments were made, indicates that the case was “not difficult,” said Pas Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
The case of Bolivia has not progressed, the last four years could contribute to the rollback.
"The issue of access to the sea has been used by the current Bolivian administration," Zarate said.
Morales' militant rhetoric undermined the remnants of Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the dialogue at some point, but after that it will be very difficult to hold discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltze, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, did not agree that the court’s decision was unusually quick.
On Monday, Bolivia will get "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile and a chance to put an end to 139 years of differences by getting mutual benefit," he said.
Calzadia also denied that Morales — still one of Latin America's most popular presidents — used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
