Languages as a subject of choice are taught in the same way as NTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), within independent school programs and in other institutions.
A survey conducted by the British Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17% of the reasons employers can’t close vacancies are due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more necessary in preparing young people for future careers.
As more and more promising positions require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if someone has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future, because this is a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who speaks several languages an advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to support a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people (15%).
That’s why investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developing countries, will provide children with a greater chance of finding a full-time job.
In Scotland, each school will learn their own languages.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the UK from a 2020 perspective, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests in independent schools, it will always be possible to choose several languages to study with qualified teachers.
Scottish independent schools try to create an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed no matter what the future holds for them.
Now it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages continue to be vital for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be considered “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
