Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
The new course at Harvard University this year has provided all its students with more sleep. This is an attempt to combat the growing culture of learning coolness all night after refilling with caffeine.
The teacher found that the world’s number one university students are often uneducated when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, has developed what he believes is the first such course in the United States.
He decided to start the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end, one girl came up to him and said, “Why am I being told this now, at the last course?”
“She told me that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” the teacher shared with The Telegraph.
At the course, which was first introduced this year, students are explained the basics of how good sleep habits help to achieve academic and sports results, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of medical services at the university, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were seriously sleep-deprived within a week.
The hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a room in the dormitory where students click cups of coffee, curtains, exercise equipment, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the effects of sleep deprivation on athletic performance, and the importance of sleep-related routines.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Next, the campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students instantly.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know about the health consequences of cigarette smoking,” added Professor Chaisler.
A culture of “wake up all night” pride still exists, he added, as well as noting that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is growing.
Sufficient sleep of good quality should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, even weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into a mode of hunger that causes constant physical hunger, he said.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaser develop the course after enrolling in one of his other courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that course opened his eyes and inspired him to create a new course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to undergo a similar training program before coming to a competitive institution.
Professor Chasler recommends students to put a reminder that you should go to bed, as well as put an alarm clock and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light”, which is emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps and can disrupt the circadian rhythm, which leads to problems with falling asleep.
