New Cancer Vaccine Could Teach Your Immune System to 'See' Cancer Cells
A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to “see” cancer cells and kill them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, which is part of the treatment
The method involves the removal of immune cells from the patient and their change in the laboratory
Then these cells are able to "see" the protein, which is common to many types of cancer. Next, these cells re-introduce the patient.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
In one woman who received a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, ovarian cancer disappeared for more than 18 months.
The method involves removing immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory so that these cells can “see” a protein common to many types of cancer (HER2), and then reintroducing these cells to the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results show that we have received a very promising vaccine.
