The launch of a new German warship has been postponed again.
The most modern frigate of the German Navy was supposed to be put into operation in 2014 instead of outdated combat vessels during the Cold War. However, according to local media, this will not happen until at least next year due to faulty systems and a rapid increase in costs.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, received from the spokesman of the military department, the commissioning of the ship "Rhineland-Palatinate", the main ship of the series of the most modern frigates of the class "Baden-Wurttemberg", was postponed until the first half of 2019.
This vessel was to join the rest of the fleet in 2014, but problems that arose after the delivery damaged the implementation of the ambitious project.
Four ships of the Baden-Wurttemberg class, which the naval department ordered in 2007, are to replace the outdated Bremen-class frigates.
It is clear that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a set of air and anti-ship missiles, as well as some technologies to reduce visibility, in particular, radar, infrared and acoustic.
Another important feature is a longer period of technical support. It is expected that the new frigates will be able not to return to the port of basing for about two years.
However, Die Zeit journalists warn that due to the constant delays, ultra-modern warships, which were supposed to increase Germany's military power at sea, will also become obsolete at the time of commissioning.
The long-suffering F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into action and returned it to Blohm + Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first return of a warship to the shipbuilding company after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but the German media mentioned significant "software and equipment defects" due to which the warship became unsuitable for military operations.
The shortcomings of the software are especially important, since the crew of the Baden-Wurttemberg class ship consists of about 120 sailors - this is only half of the number of soldiers who served on the old Bremen class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the vessel has a significant excess weight, which worsens its operational characteristics and limits the possibilities for further modernization.
The Rhineland-Palatinate frigate is believed to be twice as heavy (7,000 tons) for ships of the same class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to faulty equipment, another problem was the total cost of the project, which also includes the cost of training the crew.
The expected 2.2 billion euros turned into a colossal 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion US dollars).
Problems with obtaining new frigates have gained special weight in light of recent warnings about the decline of the German Navy.
Earlier this year, the Bundestag’s Armed Services Commissioner, Hans-Peter Bartels, said the country’s navy “remained few ships fit for combat missions.”
The official said the situation had deteriorated rapidly over time as old vessels were decommissioned and new ones did not arrive.
He expressed deep regret that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wurttemberg class were able to replenish the navy.
The National Trust will monitor the secret life of bats
The new study, which is being conducted in the Scottish Highlands, aims to establish how bats use the landscape in search of food.
Scientists hope that the data will help shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals in the future to take measures to preserve them.
In the gardens of Inverview in Wester Ross, scientists of the National Trust of Scotland will observe species such as the netopyr dwarf and netopyr pygmy, as well as common ears and water nocturnal.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations on the land to monitor bat behavior during the season.
Employees and volunteers of the National Trust of Scotland will also conduct mobile research using hand-held detectors.
Expert analysis of all recorded sounds will help to establish the frequency and ownership of bat screams.
Then it is planned to develop a detailed map of animal habitat and prepare a report to link the behavior of animals with their habitat.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor at the National Trust of Scotland, hopes the findings will help determine which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to assess the effectiveness of habitat care measures (e.g., the formation of grasslands) and determine the best methods of forest conservation for bats and other related species.
Over the past century, bat populations have declined significantly in Scotland and the UK.
They are threatened by active construction and development of territories, which deprives them of nesting places.
Other negative factors include wind installations and lighting, adhesive paper for flies, chemical treatment of building materials, and attacks of domestic cats.
They are not actually blind.
However, by hunting at night, the ears are more effective in helping them catch prey than the eyes.
They use a complex echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on the flight path.
The National Trust of Scotland, which cares for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of special importance and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bat problems very seriously.
Ten specially trained experts regularly conduct surveys, nesting sites, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland. It is located on the estate of Trive in the area of Dumfries and Galloway. It found refuge in eight of the ten species of bats living in Scotland.
Site manager David Thompson claims this is the perfect place for them.
“There are excellent conditions for bats on the territory of the estate,” he assures.
“There are old buildings, many huge trees and other favorable living conditions.
However, we still need to learn a lot about bats. Thanks to the research that we conduct here and elsewhere, we will be able to learn more about what they need to thrive."
He insists that it is very important to check the territory for the presence of bats before any technical work, since due to the unintentional destruction of one nesting site for the removal of young can kill up to 400 females with young, which is likely to lead to the destruction of the entire local population.
Sledgehammers and their nests are protected by law. The animal is forbidden to kill, torture or disturb.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Bat Conservation Centre, urged the public to join the organization's efforts.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats. We still haven't uncovered the characteristic features of populations of many species."
